          "body": "The food-and-water regulations of 4:9-12 move from posture to provisions. The bread — a mixture of six grains thrown together in one vessel — pictures desperate siege pantry management: when wheat runs out, you add barley; when barley thins, you add beans and lentils and millet and spelt. The precise rations (twenty shekels of food, a sixth of a hin of water) are not arbitrary ascetic discipline; they correspond to the caloric minimum of a besieged city. Ezekiel eats what Jerusalem will eat. But the command to bake over human dung (4:12) escalates the sign to its deepest level of defilement. In Mosaic law, human excrement was to be buried outside the camp (Deuteronomy 23:12-14) because the presence of God was in the camp and no uncleanness could defile it. To bake bread over it is to enact the total collapse of covenant purity. God interprets the sign immediately in 4:13: 'Thus will the sons of Israel eat their bread unclean among the nations where I will banish them.' The defilement of Ezekiel's bread is the defilement of exile — the state of being removed from the land of covenant and forced to live among peoples for whom no distinction between clean and unclean exists."
