          "title": "The priestly protest and divine accommodation",
          "body": "At 4:14 Ezekiel speaks for the first time in the chapter, and what he says reveals the man inside the prophet. 'Ah, Lord God! Behold, I have never been defiled.' This is not disobedience; it is the honest cry of a Levitical priest whose entire life has been organized around ritual purity, now being asked to ingest ceremonial pollution in a public act. God hears it. He grants a concession: cow's dung instead of human excrement. This small exchange carries enormous theological weight. God does not retract the command or remove the sign — its meaning must be enacted. But He shows that His commands, even the most severe, are not indifferent to the person receiving them. He can adjust the form without abandoning the content. This is not weakness; it is the pastoral precision of the same God who, two verses later, pronounces that He will break the staff of bread in Jerusalem. He is simultaneously immovable in judgment and attentive to His servant. Calvin observed here that God 'does not tyrannize over His servants, but consults their weakness as a father.'"
