          "title": "The closing oracle — from sign to sentence",
          "body": "The chapter's final two verses (4:16-17) translate the enacted prophecy into explicit judicial sentence. God will 'break the staff of bread in Jerusalem' — the staff (*matteh*) of bread is a Pentateuchal image (Leviticus 26:26; Psalm 105:16) for bread as the support of life; to break it is to remove the basic provision of existence. The people will eat by weight and drink by measure — the exact conditions Ezekiel has been enacting. They will be 'appalled with one another,' each looking at his neighbor's face and seeing his own desolation mirrored there. And they will 'waste away in their iniquity' — the chapter's final word. The connection between sin and consequence is not mechanical fate; it is the judgment of a covenant God who has warned, counted, and now enacted. The chapter that began with a clay brick and a prophet lying on the ground ends with a city whose bread is broken and whose people are rotting in the guilt that caused their destruction. The sign has become the sentence."
