        "excerpt": "Lie down on your left side and lay the iniquity of the house of Israel on it; you shall bear their iniquity for the number of days that you lie on it.",
        "body": "The second sign-act is the chapter's most theologically dense. Ezekiel is commanded to lie immobile on his left side for 390 days (bearing Israel's iniquity) and then on his right side for 40 days (bearing Judah's iniquity), with ropes preventing any movement. The day-for-a-year formula (4:6) makes the prophet's body a temporal map of covenant history: every day he lies there represents a year of accumulated rebellion.\n\nThe 390-year figure has generated sustained exegetical discussion. The most contextually coherent reading (Greenberg, *Ezekiel 1-20*, Anchor Bible) takes it as running from the division of the monarchy under Rehoboam (c. 930 BC) to the end of the northern kingdom (722 BC) and beyond, encompassing the full span of Israel's independent rebellion. The 40-year figure for Judah is less disputed — it likely refers to the period from Josiah's death and Judah's final apostasy (609 BC) to the end of the exile (c. 570-540 BC). What is theologically non-negotiable in the text is the precision: God has been counting. The rebellion is not vague or impressionistic; it has a beginning, a duration, and an end that God has measured.\n\nThe verb *nasa* (bear) is the chapter's most theologically resonant word. It is the Levitical term for priestly bearing of guilt — Aaron and his sons 'bear' the iniquity of the sanctuary (Numbers 18:1); the scapegoat 'bears' all the iniquities of Israel into the wilderness (Leviticus 16:22). Ezekiel is a priest (1:3). His lying on his side is a priestly act — not a substitutionary atonement (which only the death of Christ accomplishes, Hebrews 9:26-28) but a representational bearing, a somatic identification with the sin-weight of the people. Isaiah 53:4-6 uses the same verb of the Servant who 'bore our griefs.' Ezekiel foreshadows at the level of sign-act what the Servant will accomplish at the level of historical reality.\n\nThe ropes of 4:8 complete the sign: Ezekiel cannot abandon his post. He is as bound to the duration of this bearing as Israel is bound to its consequence. The bared arm of 4:7 adds a final element — the exposed arm is the posture of combat readiness (Deuteronomy 4:34; Isaiah 52:10), here turned in hostility against the city the prophet once called home.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nasa* (bear, 4:4-6) — Levitical guilt-bearing verb; see Leviticus 16:22; Numbers 18:1; Isaiah 53:4. *Avon* (iniquity) — moral perversity, the accumulated guilt of deliberate deviation; not a single sin but a condition. *Avot* (ropes, 4:8) — braided cords; the plural suggests multiple bindings, total immobility. *Zeroa chasaph* (bared arm, 4:7) — exposed for work or warfare; God's 'outstretched arm' of judgment in Deuteronomy 4:34 uses the same idiom."
