        "body": "The third sign-act moves from posture to provisions. The six-grain mixture of 4:9 is not a dietary prescription; it is a picture of siege-time pantry desperation. In normal times one baked with wheat or barley — a single grain. The mixture of whatever was available signals the progressive exhaustion of food stores under siege conditions. The bread is to be eaten over 390 days in strict daily rations: twenty shekels of food (roughly 8 ounces) and a sixth of a hin of water (roughly a pint). These are subsistence quantities — enough to survive but not enough to live with dignity or strength. The precision of the numbers is part of the sign: Ezekiel does not eat approximately; he eats exactly what Jerusalem will eat.\n\nThe command to bake over human dung (4:12) is where the sign-act reaches its most offensive point, and that offensiveness is the point. Deuteronomy 23:12-14 commanded that human waste be buried outside the camp because God walked in the camp and no uncleanness was to defile His presence. To use it as fuel for bread-baking violates the most basic covenant purity regulation. The act is deliberately revolting because what it signifies is revolting: Israel eating defiled bread 'among the nations where I will banish them' (4:13). Exile is not just geographic displacement; it is ritual defilement — the removal from the land of covenant purity into the domain of the nations where the Mosaic distinctions between clean and unclean no longer operate practically. Ezekiel's bread is the taste of that defilement.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Uggah* (barley cake, 4:12) — a flat round bread, the most basic form of bread preparation. *Gelel* (dung, 4:12, 15) — specifically dried excrement; BSB renders it 'excrement.' *Tame* (defiled, 4:13) — Levitical uncleanness; the same root appears in Ezekiel's protest at 4:14. *Goy* (nations, 4:13) — the pagan peoples, the anti-Covenant context into which Israel will be scattered."
