        "excerpt": "But I said, 'Ah, Lord God! Behold, I have never been defiled… Then He said to me, See, I will give you cow's dung in place of human dung.'",
        "body": "Ezekiel has been silent throughout the chapter's commands. Here, for the first and only time, he speaks — and what he says reveals the man God has chosen. The exclamation *Ahah Adonai Yehovih* ('Ah, Lord God') is an ejaculation of dismayed protest, the same cry that punctuates Jeremiah's complaints (Jeremiah 1:6; 4:10; 14:13) and Ezekiel's own inaugural vision (9:8; 11:13). It is not rebellious refusal; it is honest anguish. Ezekiel names his lifelong priestly discipline: from youth to the present day, he has observed the Mosaic food laws scrupulously. He has not eaten *nevelah* (what died of itself) or *terephah* (what was torn by beasts) or *piggul* (forbidden meat). Now God is asking him to bake with human excrement — an act that would defile not just his food but his priestly identity.\n\nThe exchange that follows is one of the most intimate in the book. God hears the protest and grants a concession: cow's dung instead of human excrement. This is not capitulation; the substance of the sign remains. Bread will still be baked over animal waste — unusual and unclean — and the message of exile-defilement still stands. But God reduces the degree of defilement in response to His servant's legitimate priestly concern. The adjustment preserves both the message and the messenger.\n\nTheologically, this passage contributes to the broader canonical portrait of a God who commands absolutely but pastors personally (cf. 1 Kings 19:1-8, where God provides food for an exhausted Elijah before commanding further ministry). It also illuminates the dynamic of prophetic intercession: Ezekiel does not simply transmit divine messages — he exists in a genuine dialogical relationship with God in which his own personhood and history are taken into account. Calvin's comment is apt: 'God does not tyrannize over His servants, but consults their weakness as a father.' The concession also serves a secondary interpretive function: it shows that the sign-acts are not arbitrary cruelty but purposeful communication. When the purpose can be preserved with less damage to the prophet, God adjusts the method."
